<%= faq_schema([
  { question: "Why does pitch rate matter?", answer: "Underpitching yeast leads to slow starts, stuck fermentations, off flavors from stressed yeast, and excessive ester or fusel alcohol production. Overpitching produces clean but underexpressive fermentation, with reduced ester and phenol character that some styles depend on. Hitting the right cell count gives you predictable fermentation timing, full attenuation, and the flavor profile the style demands." },
  { question: "What pitch rate should I use?", answer: "The Chris White / White Labs standard is 0.75 million cells per milliliter per degree Plato for ales and 1.5 million cells per milliliter per degree Plato for lagers. High-gravity beers above 1.060 OG should bump to 1.0 million per mL per °P for ales and 2.0 million per mL per °P for lagers. The math becomes total cells in billions equals pitch rate times volume in mL times Plato divided by 1000." },
  { question: "How many cells are in a packet of dry yeast?", answer: "An 11-gram packet of fresh dry yeast contains approximately 220 billion viable cells, or 20 billion cells per gram. Dry yeast loses about 21 percent viability per month at room temperature, so a packet that is six months old contains roughly 130 billion viable cells. Refrigeration slows the decline. Most packets are date-stamped so you can estimate viability accurately." },
  { question: "How big a starter do I need?", answer: "A 1-liter stir-plate starter inoculated with one fresh 100-billion-cell smack pack typically grows to about 200 billion cells, a 2x growth factor. For a 5-gallon ale at 1.050 OG you need about 175 billion cells, so a 1-liter starter is sufficient. For a 5-gallon lager at the same OG you need 350 billion cells and a 2-liter starter, or two packs without a starter." },
  { question: "Can I just pitch a single dry packet?", answer: "For a 5-gallon ale below 1.060 OG, yes. One fresh 11-gram packet of dry ale yeast contains roughly 220 billion viable cells, which exceeds the 175 billion needed. For lagers, high gravity beers, or older yeast, plan to pitch two packets or build a starter." }
]) %>

